Intorduction

  • Radioactive Decay Series: A sequence of radioactive decays that proceed until a stable isotope is formed.
  • Alignment with CLOs: Understand the mechanisms and significance of decay series in geology.

Radioactive Decay Series

  • Definition: A chain of successive radioactive decays from an unstable parent isotope to a stable daughter isotope.
  • Key Concept: Each decay series progresses through a series of alpha and beta decays.

Natural Decay Series (1)

  • Three Principal Natural Decay Series:
    1. Uranium-238 Series (Uranium Series)
      • Ends with Lead-206.
    2. Uranium-235 Series (Actinium Series)
      • Ends with Lead-207.
    3. Thorium-232 Series (Thorium Series)
      • Ends with Lead-208.

Radioactive Decay Series (2)

Part of the chart of the nuclides, in terms of Z against N, to show species in the Th- and U-series decay chains and their half-lives., Source: Dickin, A. P. (2018)

Parent-Daughter Relationships

  • Transformation Process:
    • Parent isotopes decay into daughter isotopes, which may themselves be radioactive.
  • Significance:
    • Understanding these relationships helps in dating rocks and minerals.

Geochronological Application

U-Pb Dating Method

  • Principle: Measures the ratio of uranium isotopes to lead isotopes.
  • Uses:
    • Dating zircon crystals in igneous rocks.

Importance

  • Accuracy: One of the most precise radiometric dating methods.
  • Half-Lives:
    • U-238: ~4.5 billion years.
    • U-235: ~704 million years.

Branching Decay

  • Definition: Occurs when a radioactive isotope decays via more than one decay mode.
  • Impact: Adds complexity to decay of radioactive isotopes.

Example

  • Bismuth-212 can decay by:
    • Alpha Decay to Thallium-208.
    • Beta Decay to Polonium-212.
  • Rubidium-87 can decay by:
    • Beta-minus decay (99.999% probability) to Strontium-87 (Sr-87).
    • electron capture (tiny fraction <0.001%) to Krypton-87 (Kr-87), though this has minimal practical significance in dating.

Health and Environmental Impact

Radon Gas (Rn-222)

  • Origin: Part of the Uranium-238 decay series.
  • Characteristics:
    • Colorless, odorless, radioactive gas.
    • Can accumulate in buildings, especially basements.
  • Health Risks:
    • Leading cause of lung cancer among non-smokers.
  • Mitigation Measures:
    • Ventilation systems.
    • Regular radon testing in homes and workplaces.

Would the release of Radon-222 (Rn-222) affect the Uranium-238 decay chain?

  • Radon-222 is a noble gas produced from the decay of Radium-226.
  • Being a gas, Rn-222 can escape from rocks, soils, and groundwater into the atmosphere.

Effect of Rn-222 Release

  • Rn-222 has a half-life of 3.8 days and decays into Polonium-218 (Po-218).
  • If Rn-222 escapes, the decay chain is temporarily interrupted in the local environment.
  • However, the overall decay chain continues where Rn-222 remains or has already decayed.

Impact on Radiometric Dating

  • Rn-222 escape can result in loss of parent isotopes, potentially affecting the accuracy of dating methods (e.g., U-238 to Pb-206).
  • Accurate dating may require careful consideration of radon release, particularly in open systems.
